Jonah Rzadzinski Matranga (born Jonah Sonz Matranga, August 11, 1969, Brookline, Massachusetts) is a singer, songwriter, and guitarist who has released a variety of solo material under his own name and onelinedrawing, and has previously been part of the bands Far and New End Original (an anagram of "onelinedrawing") and Gratitude.
He now continues to work and tour under onelinedrawing'.
He left in 1987 to attend Pitzer College in Claremont, California, where he majored in English and began making music by himself.
After graduation, he moved to Sacramento to form Far in 1991.
They made four albums, including the classic Water and Solutions, before disbanding in December 1998.
During this time, Jonah married in April 1994, and his daughter was born that August.
During this time, Jonah married in April 1994, and his daughter was born that August.
He divorced two years later.
In 1999, he moved to the Bay Area.
He currently lives in San Francisco, making music and raising his daughter.
He released two EPs in 1999 (Sketchy EPs #1 and #2) of bedroom demos.

sentences: Jonah has contributed backup vocals to War All the Time (by Thursday) on the track "Steps Ascending", and to the Deftones's acoustic remix version of "Be Quiet and Drive (Far Away)" and a cover of Sade's song "No Ordinary Love", both of which the Deftones released as b-sides (also, several Deftones members contributed to Far's cover of the Jawbox song "Savory").
In 2005 he co-wrote "Calling" for Taproot, the first single from their album Blue-Sky Research.
Jonah returned to the onelinedrawing name in 2012 for Audio Antihero label's "Some.
Jonah sung backing vocals for Zebulon-Raleigh, North Carolina based songwriter Nick Driver's independent release Poets' Corner Volume One track titled "Universal Love" in late 2012.
In August 2021, UK stoner/post-rock band Sons of Alpha Centauri released their latest album Push featuring Jonah as guest vocalist on all nine tracks.

The Three Sketchys (1999-2005) is an anthology containing the contents of three albums:
Sketchy EP #1 by Onelinedrawing (1999)
Sketchy EP #2 by Onelinedrawing (2000)
Sketchy EP #3 by Jonah Matranga (2005)along with a bonus track: a new mix of "The Big Parade" from Sketchy EP #2.
The recordings span 1999–2005 and are described by the artist as a collection of "homemade" tracks spanning several years.
